{"cursor":"4990","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In mathematics, in particular in algebra, 'polarization' is a technique for\nexpressing a homogeneous polynomial in a simpler fashion by adjoining more\nvariables. Specifically, given a homogeneous polynomial, polarization produces a\nmultilinear form from which the original polynomial can be recovered by\nevaluating along a certain diagonal.\n\nAlthough the technique is deceptively simple, it has applications in many areas\nof abstract mathematics: in particular to algebraic geometry, invariant theory,\nand representation theory. Polarization and related techniques form the\nfoundations for Weyl's invariant theory.\n","linknr":112,"url":"Polarization_of_an_algebraic_form","recorded":1362903893,"links":10,"instances":["mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Abstract algebra","Homogeneous polynomials"],"headings":["The technique","Examples","Mathematical details and consequences","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/9/5/795ccb62b077427cbe330063ba5845f7.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/c/9/7c9e64f773d0e79543aede64ebc257c1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/b/9/5b95363a1ec3556f6486126bfeef0759.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/9/4/094875f14cbf6488a8341f1fc04183ce.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/0/d/e0d4f1f905c55fb98a4723cfef67f235.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/d/2/3d28ff309bb934c384bf41ec7b80d36c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/f/a/ffa5f834490bc57837b9b56423cd0cc2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/8/4/c84bd351117106e1ed6c3da086f8eefa.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["field","mathematics"]],"members":["field"],"related":["Mathematics","Algebra","Homogeneous_polynomial","Multilinear_form","Algebraic_geometry","Invariant_theory","Representation_theory","Weyl's_invariant_theory","Indeterminate","Quadratic_form","Polarization_identity","Commutative_ring","Field_(mathematics)","Characteristic_zero","Polynomial_ring","Graded_ring","Degree_of_a_polynomial","Symmetric_power","Symmetric_algebra","Positive_characteristic","Topological_vector_space","Claudio_Procesi"]}